Polynomial Regression¶

By Audrey Nguyen¶

OVERVIEW¶

  1. Using Polynomial Regression for Non-Linear Regression problem.
  2. The data from the file PolynomialRegressionData_I.csv was plotted using matplotlib.
  3. A PolynomialFeatures transformation was performed, then linear regression was performed to calculate the optimal ordinary least squares regression model parameters.
  4. The first figure was recreated by adding the best fit curve to all subplots.
  5. The true model parameters were inferred.

#=================================
# WHERE TO SAVE THE FIGURES METHOD
#=================================
PROJECT_ROOT_DIR = "."
FOLDER = "figures"
IMAGES_PATH = os.path.join(PROJECT_ROOT_DIR, FOLDER)
os.makedirs(IMAGES_PATH, exist_ok=True)
def save_fig(fig_id, tight_layout=True, fig_extension="png", resolution=300):
    path = os.path.join(IMAGES_PATH, fig_id + "." + fig_extension)
    print("Saving figure", fig_id)
    if tight_layout:
        plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(path, format=fig_extension, dpi=resolution)

TRAINING LINEAR REGRESSION MODEL ON NON LINEAR DATA¶

ACTUALLY, NON LINEAR FEATURE DATA TRANSFORMED TO POLYNOMIAL FEATURE DATA. THE LINEAR REGRESSION MODEL TRAINS ON TRANSFORMED POLYNOMIAL FEATURE DATA AND NON-TRANSFORMED TARGET DATA.

TRANSFORMING NON-LINEAR FEATURE DATA TO POLYNOMIAL FEATURE DATA¶

In [4]:
#==========================
# FEATURE DATA FROM DATASET
#==========================
#The 'x' and 'y' are the feature data.
#Select data in columns 'x' and 'y' as feature data dropping columns 'z' from dataset
PolynomialRegressionData_I_Features = PolynomialRegressionData_I.drop("z", axis=1)  

#========================
# lABEL DATA FROM DATASET
#========================
#The 'z' is the response data.
#The data from 'z' coloumn is return as targets
PolynomialRegressionData_I_Targets = PolynomialRegressionData_I["z"].copy()
In [5]:
#==============================
# DATA CLEANING FEATURE DATASET
#==============================

#Finding rows with null values
sample_incomplete_rows = PolynomialRegressionData_I_Features[PolynomialRegressionData_I_Features.isnull().any(axis=1)].head()

#Get median values
x_median = PolynomialRegressionData_I_Features["x"].median()   
y_median = PolynomialRegressionData_I_Features["y"].median()   
                                                
#Fill in null values, if any, with median values
sample_incomplete_rows["x"].fillna(x_median, inplace=True) 
sample_incomplete_rows["y"].fillna(y_median, inplace=True)
In [6]:
#===============================================================
# TRANSFORM EACH RAW FEATURE TO SECOND DEGREE POLYNOMIAL FEATURE
#===============================================================

#Instantiate object of PolynomialFeatures class:
#Polynomial degree is set to 2. Bias term (intercept) is not included
#in the model itself beause linear regression model will generate that. 
poly_features = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2, include_bias=False)   

#Fit, train, and transform feature data set to polynomials
X_poly = poly_features.fit_transform(PolynomialRegressionData_I_Features)

TRAINING LINEAR REGRESSION MODEL ON TRANSFORMED POLYNOMIAL FEATURE DATA¶

TRAIN ON TRANSFORMED POLYNOMIAL FEATURE DATA AND NON-TRANSFORMED TARGET DATA.

In [7]:
#================================================================
# TRAIN LINEAR REGRESSION MODEL ON TRANSFORMED POLYNOMIAL FEATURE
#================================================================

#Instantiate object of LinearRegresssion class
model = LinearRegression()                              

#fit and train model with transformed polynomial features and non-transformed target values
model.fit(X_poly, PolynomialRegressionData_I_Targets)

CREATING SECOND IMAGE OF DATA AND PREDICTIVE LINE¶

RECREATE RAW 3D SCATTERPLOTS OF THE 'PolynomialRegressionData_I' DATA AND PLOT PREDICTIVE LINE OF BEST FIT

USING THE x_fit AND y_fit DATA TO COMPUTE z_fit BY INVOKING THE LINEAR REGRESSION MODEL'S predict() METHOD. THIS ALLOWS THE PLOTTING OF THE LINE OF BEST FIT THAT IS PREDICTED BY THE MODEL.

GENERATE 'x_fit' AND 'y_fit' FEATURE DATA USING linspace() METHOD¶

In [9]:
#=================
# DATA FOR 3D LINE
#=================
#Generate x_fit and y_fit feature data using linspace()
x_fit = np.linspace(-21,21,1000)              #'x_fit' numpy array 
y_fit = x_fit                                 #'y_fit' numpy array

TRANSFORM FEATURE DATA TO POLYNOMIAL FEATURE DATA¶

In [10]:
#================================================================================================================
# TRANSFORM x_fit AND y_fit, WHICH ARE COMBINED IN A DATAFRAME, BEFORE PASSING TO PREDICT METHOD TO GET THE z_fit
#================================================================================================================

#COMBINE x_fit AND y_fit INTO A DATAFRAME
x_fit_y_fit_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['x_fit','y_fit'])   #create DataFrame with columns: x_fit and y_fit
x_fit_y_fit_df['x_fit'] = x_fit.tolist()                   #add 'x_fit' array as new column in DataFrame
x_fit_y_fit_df['y_fit'] = y_fit.tolist()                   #add 'y_fit' array as new column in DataFrame

#Instantiate object of PolynomialFeatures class:
#Polynomial degree is set to 2. The bias term (intercept) is not included
#in the model itself beause linear regression model will generate that. 
poly_features_fit = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2, include_bias=False) 

#Fit, train, and transform feature data set to polynomials
X_poly_fit = poly_features_fit.fit_transform(x_fit_y_fit_df)

GET 'z_fit' FROM LINEAR REGRESSION'S PREDICTIONS MADE ON POLYNOMIAL FEATURE DATA¶

In [11]:
#====================================================
# GET z_fit USING PREDICT METHOD IN LINEAR REGRESSION 
#====================================================

#z_fit, another data for 3D line resulted from:
#x_fit and y_fit as features passed together as a X_poly_fit to the model's predict() method, which returns z_fit
z_fit = model.predict(X_poly_fit)
